Dear Colleagues:

As I mentioned verbally to a couple of you, I would like to recruit more  students in an elective I am teaching this semester, ‚ÄúConcurrent Object-Oriented Programming with SCOOP‚Äù. The research-oriented topic is the same as that of my ‚ÄúConcurrency Made Easy‚Äù ERC Advanced Investigator Grant. Only two students registered, but I think more might be interested, so I would be most grateful if you could advertise the opportunity to your students.

The course description is attached. Note that this is the proposal I submitted to the administration and some of the details of the course delivery (number of hours etc.) have been tuned since then, but the syllabus and other information remains accurate.

It is a project-based course involving a significant, although reasonable, amount of programming. The topic for the project is simple: pick a concurrent programming problem for which there is not yet a published SCOOP/Eiffel solution on the Rosetta Code site, http://rosettacode.org, and produce a solution that can be submitted to this site, and (ideally) accepted.

The course has sessions on Tuesday and Wednesday (of some weeks only, corresponding to my presence here). If any student has conflicts with other classes, I am sure we can resolve them informally.

Students joining now will not have missed anything since the first lecture will take place next Tuesday only: this week one of the two students enrolled, a Spaniard, had just received his visa and was not in Kazan yet, so I decided to wait for him and find time later in the semester to compensate for the first week. My hope is that with your help we can attract a few more people.

Feel free to stop by my office today or tomorrow if you need any more information.

Thanks in advance!

I guess, that some of you have already recieved this news, but I duplicate it here

The news are about thesis grading.

According to the information given from thesis supervisors, the grades for thesis work will be provided as follows:
- If you submit your thesis paper to given list of top conferences and thesis will become accepted - you get A grade
- You get B grade, if you successfully submit paper for another list of conferences (attached below) 
- C grade will be received if you don't submit paper to any conference
- D grade, if you don't finish your work

This leads to several consequences:
- You need to choose your level (A or B) before submission - one paper can't be submitted to several conferences at a time
-  Since accepting takes several months - the paper should be submitted before the end of January, so we have at most 5 months for the work
